public java.nio.ByteBuffer getByteBuffer()
Returns the current buffer to read or write from, with the position reset to zero. The endian-ness of the buffer and of the underlying system has been accounted for. Note that input buffers isInput() are read-only.

write

public void write(float[] output)
A convenience method to write a float array of samples to the output. The array values are expected to be bounded to the range of [-1,1]. The need to convert to the correct sample type is abstracted. The output array should be same size as the buffer. If it is larger, then a BufferOverflowException will be thrown. If it is smaller, the buffer will be incompletely filled. If the ASIO host does not use floats to represent samples, then the AsioChannel's ByteBuffer should be directly manipulated. Use getByteBuffer to access the buffer.

Parameters:
output - A float array to write to the output.

read

public void read(float[] input)
A convenience method to read samples from the input buffer to a float array. The argument array must have the same length as the configured buffer size. The returned samples are bounded to within [-1,1]. The input array should be the same size as the input array. If it larger, then a BufferUnderflowException will be thrown. If it is smaller, then the buffer will be incompletely read.

Parameters:
input - A float array to read into.
